Nobody told me EOA wallets were a dead end for agents.
I had to figure it out by trying to build one.
Here's what broke — and what ERC-4337 fixes.

The problem with EOA wallets for agents:
— One private key controls everything. No spending limits, no rules
— Can't batch transactions. Each action = a separate gas fee
— No gas sponsorship. Agent always needs ETH in its pocket
— Zero on-chain audit trail. No record of what the agent actually did

This is why ERC-4337 exists. Here's exactly how it works:

1. The agent creates a UserOperation — not a raw transaction. It's a packaged intent: calldata, gas limits, signature, paymaster info. All in one struct.
2. The UserOp goes into an alt mempool — a separate P2P network. No changes to Ethereum's core protocol needed. Ever.
3. A Bundler picks it up. Simulates it locally first (if it fails here, it never hits the chain). Bundles multiple UserOps into one Ethereum transaction. Submits to the EntryPoint.
4. The EntryPoint contract validates it — calls validateUserOp() on your smart account, confirms the signature and gas deposit, then executes the action.
5. The smart account runs the operation within whatever rules you programmed — spend caps, time locks, multi-sig requirements.
The part that hit me hardest: Bundlers are the only actors in this whole system that still need an EOA. Everyone else works through smart accounts.
That's the quiet revolution inside ERC-4337. It doesn't kill EOAs. It just makes them irrelevant for everyone except the infrastructure layer.
And the Paymaster? That's what lets a protocol sponsor your agent's gas entirely. Your agent acts. Someone else pays. That unlocks a whole new design space for autonomous DeFi.
This is the plumbing beneath every agent wallet you'll ever build.
